HEADWORD: Troglodyte
<hw>Trog"lo*dyte</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>troglodytae</ets>, pl., Gr. <?/ one who creeps into holes; <?/ a
hole, cavern (fr. <?/ to gnaw) + <?/ enter: cf. F.
<ets>troglodyte</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Ethnol.)</fld> <def>One
of any savage race that dwells in caves, instead of constructing
dwellings; a cave dweller, or cave man. Most of the primitive races of
man were troglodytes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the <qex>troglodytes'</qex> country there is a lake, for the
hurtful water it beareth called the ⟦ldquo⟧mad lake.⟦rdquo⟧</q>
<rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>An anthropoid ape, as the
chimpanzee.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The wren.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Troglodytes</ent>⟦br⟧
